{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060057A/1930102401/0524.xml":{"full_text":"A-4\nJOB HIT PLACED\nt FIRST BY WOODS\nExpects Relief Machinery to\nBe \u201cUnder Full Steam\nWithin Week.\u201d\n(Continued Prom First Pege.)\nare making redoubled efforts at em\nployment through the departments,\nand this work will be pushed to the\nutmost. Thi? problem Is one that can\nbe answered only if the whole country\ntakes a hand at it. National unity\nin action and organization is the only\nforce that cen bring the answer. With\n120.000.000 people in the United States,\nwith our resources, our ability for or\nganization and cur loyalty, we can\ntake care of the comparatively small\nfraction that are unemployed and may\nsuffer from want and privation as cold\nweather comes on.\n\"What is needed is recognition of the\nobligations of every man ana woman to\nhis neighbor and to use this in team\nwork to carry through the Winter.\u201d\nCol. Woods said he was seeking the\naccurate number of unemployed.\n\"We expect to get information from\neach city,\u201d he added, \u201cand pass it to\nother cities, paiticularly as to success\nful methods used in combatting the un\nemployment problem.\n\u201cWe want to know all about labor\nconditions, those working on part time\nand the number of families left with no\nbreadwinner. It is only on\ninformation that wise action can be\ntaken.\u201d\nHe said information also would be\nsought from the Census Bureau, the\nAmerican Federation of Labor and State\nlabor and cth*r agencies.\nQuestioned whether it would be nec\nessary for President Hoover to con\nvene Congress in special session a\nmonth before the December session.\nCol. Woods said, \u201cMy preliminary judg\nment is that a special session of Con\negress is not necessary-\u201d He added,\nhowever, that if the Cabinet Commit\ntee, with the aid of States and cities,\nwas unable to remedy the situation a\nspecial session might be considered.\nDenial Made at White House.\nDenial was made at the White House\nthat the President intended calling a\nspecial session.\nAlthough it had been indicated that\nthe Chief Executive would ask Congress\nto remove restrictions upon certain\npublic work so as to advance the con\nstruction pregram, it was said he would\nwait for the regular session.\nCol. Woods said he expected the\nrelief machinery to be \u201coperating un\nder full, f team within a week.\u201d\nHe was pleased to note industry gen\nerally was co-operating through the\nadoption of the stagger system of em\nployment.\nIt will not be necessary for the Fed\neral Government to set up a bread\nline, he said, adding the feeding .of\nUnemployed was a local problem.\nMaj. Gen. Lytle Brown, chief of\nArmy Engineers, announced today that\nall matters involving labor along the\nMississippi and Missouri Rivers were\nbeing handled with the greatest dis\npatch to keep in employment as many\nmen as possible.\nThe general\u2019s announcement was\nmade in connection with reports that\ncontracts for w'ork on th? rivers were\nbeing held up in the War Depart\nment, causing the laying off of men\nhired by contractors to furnish piling?.\nSteps Taken on AH Sides.\nFrom every side today came news of\nsteps being taken without awaiting the\nsetup of a central organization. Not\nonly business men and industrialists,\nbut great numbers of workers were\nregistering their willingness to con\ntribute aid. Two Government branches\ntook \u00abteps to help in a small but sub\nstant\\l way, the Post Office ordering\nall overtime eliminated and the work\ngiven to substitutes, while the Shipping\nBoard announced it would \u201cforget,\u201d for\nthe time being, the plan to cut down\nthe Merchant Fleet Corporation's staff\nin Washington and elsewhere. Alto\ngether this cut would have laid off\ncome 700 employes at a saving ap\nproximating $1,000,000. These workers\nare scattered at various ports where\nstaffs are not considered essential any\nlonger.\nThe number affected by the post\noffice order has not yet been deter\nmined, but is to be made knowm short\nly. At present a good many regular\nemployes are making 65 cents an hour\nfor the time beyond the eight-hour\nperiod.\nUpward Trend Is Shown.\nThe Reserve Board\u2019s summary of\nbusiness and financial conditions for\nSeptember found that after the sub\nstantial decrease in factory output from\nMay to August, September had shown\nan upward trend, which did not, how\never, reach former production figures\nfor the same month. Employment in\nfactories also increased, though less\nthan the usual gain for this season of\nthe year. Residential construction was\nsaid to have increased materially.\nThe chief gains in employment came\nfrom the fruit and vegetable canning\nand the clothing industries and from\nretail establishments and coal mines.\nEmployment dropped in iron, steel, au\ntomobile and lumber industries, and so\ndid their production. The production\ngains were shown chiefly in textiles,\ncoal and copper.\nt Suggestions reaching the Farm Board\nthat it\u2019s supply of wheat be turned over\nto feeding the jobless drew from Chair\nman Legge the statement the board\nwould be glad to do so if Congress!\nwould reimburse it for the cost of the\ngrain, which was acquired in stabiliza-\ntion operations.\nExtension of the \u201cstagger\u201d system of i\nemploying more workers for fewer days\nor hours a week, was undertaken by j\nArmy Engineers in charge of flood con- j\ntrol works at the instance of Secretary:\nHurley.\n\nHOOVER PRAISED\nFOR AIDING LABOR:\nResolution Adopted by Kiwanis\nClub Commending His Efforts to\nRelieve Unemployment.\nA resolution indorsing President\nHoover's efforts to relieve existing un\nemployment conditions in this country\nwas unanimously passed by the kiwanis\nClub, meeting yesterday at the Wash\nington Hotel.\nThe resolution points out that un\nemployment is a deterring factor In the\nrevival of business conditions through\nout the country and lauds the Presi\ndent for his action in appointing a\nspecial commission to examine the\npresent situation and devise ways and\nmeans to alleviate those conditions.\nThe resolution calls upon Kiwanis\nInternational to co-operate with the\nPresident in his efforts. The resolu\ntion will be presented before the Capi\ntal District Convention of the Kiwanis\nClub now in session at Virginia Beach.\nA series of short talks in which naval\nofficers explained the part each took in\nbuilding up the Navy was followed by\na brief address by Charles F. Adams,\nSecretary of the Navy, in which he told\nof the growth of the service and de\nscribed its functionings.\nOthers who spoke were: Maj. Gen.\nBen H. Fuller, commandant of the\nMarine Corps; Admiral F. B. Upham,\nchief of the Bureau of Navigation;\nAdmiral George H. Rock, chief of the\nBureau of Construction and Repair;\nAdmiral John Halllgan, assistant chief\nof Naval Operations; Capt. John W.\nGreenslade, aide to the Secretary of the\nNavy; Capt. H. A. Baldridge, chief of\nthe Office of Naval Intelligence, and\n\u2018Capt. C. C. Block, commandant of the\nWa\u00bbh|ngton Navy Yard.\nIDLE MAY SHARE $6,272,000\nSET ASIDE FOR YULE MAIL JOBS\nPest Up\nPlan to Give 210,000 Tern\n-1 porary Work.\nMooney Will Exclude All But\nNeedy and Civil Service\nEligibles.\nA plan whereby only those without\njGbs will bs allowed the opportunity to\nshaie in the $6,272,003 set aside for\nthe employment of extra help for the\nhandling of the Christmas mail\ntnroughout the country was under con\nsideration at the Post Office Depart\nment today following the announce\nment of Postmaster William M. Mooney\nhere that only the needy joble s would\nget Christmas jobs at the local post\noffice after the eligibles under the Civil\nService have been taken care of.\nPost Office Department officials today\nestimated that if the Washington post\nmaster\u2019s plan is adopted, the Christmas\nholiday mail rush will provide tem\nporary employment for more than 210,-\n000 of the country\u2019s great army of the\njobless.\nThe $6,272,000 has been set aside, for\nthe employment of temporary clerks,\ncarriers and laborers, to carry the post\noffices of the country over their annual\nChristmas \u201cpeak load.\u201d\n\u2018First Come* Basis Used.\nHeretofore the temporary positions\nhave been given on a \u201cfirst come, first\nseived\u201d basis, after those eligible but\njobless under the Civil Service rules had\nbeen given their opportunity to accept\nor reject the temporary employment.\nThe jobs, distributed throughout the\nentire country, are expected to provide\na welcome step-gap for those who get\nthem, at the time when they will need\nwork and money most.\nPestmaster Mconey this morning an\nnounced that every effort will be made\nat the local Post Office to see that the\njobless Washingtonian gets his oppor\ntunity to work temporarily at the Post\nOffice during the holiday rush.\nThere will be places for about 2,200\ntemporary employes in the local post\noffice during the rush period, the post\nmaster estimates, on the basis of last\nyear\u2019s holiday business. There arc\nabout 1,300 clerks and carriers on\nwhat Is known as the Civil Service eli\ngible list at the post office, composed\nof persons seeking positions with ihe\npost office who ha\\e oecome eligible by\nexamination. The majority of these\napplicants, however, already are work\ning, many of them in other Govern\nment departments, and cannot take\nadvantage of the temporary jobs at the\npost office. An average of about 20 per\ncent of these eligibles, Mr. Mooney esti\nmates, are without jobs and take the\ntemporary work. This offering of work\nto the Civil Service eligibles is manda\ntory, Mr. Mooney says, but will not cut\nout any who are already unemployed,\nfor those who are now employed will\nnot leave a regular position for tempo\nrary work over the Christmas holidays.\nHundreds of Students Apply.\nMr. Mooney today said he particu\nlarly wants to stress the point that the\nneedy deserve the opportunity to earn\nthe Christmas money upon the parents\nof high school and college youths, who\nheretolore have gotten the bulk of the\ntemporary jobs at the post office. There\nare now in the post office here hun\ndreds of applications from college\nyouths and school boys for Christmas\nwork.\n\u201cThe times are such,\" said Mr.\nMooney, \u201cthat where a family U able\nto send a boy to school or college, the\nboy should withdraw from competition\nwith those who actually need jobs to\npay for their food and shelter. The un\nemployment situation is serious, and\nthere is every reason why those who\ncan get along without the work should\nstand aside while those who need the\nwork badly do it.\"\nLast year the city post office paid\nout about $60,000 to 2,200 temporary\nemployes, and plans are being laid this\nyear to pay out at least that much to\nthj temporary workers. Last year the\naverage total wage to temporary work\ners, at 65 cents an hour during the\nINSULL UTILITIES\nTO HELP JOBLESS\nOne Day's Pay Per Month for Six\nMonths to Be Given by\nEmployes.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, October 24.\u2014Dollars from\nthe pay checks of officers and employes\nof the Insull utility companies promised\ntoday a potent fund to fight distress\nduring the Winter months.\nSamuel Insull, head of the group,\nannounced that one day's pay a month\nfor six months would be given in volun\ntary contributions by the entire per\nsonnel of his organization.\n\"The appeal has been made to em\nployes and office:s alike,\u201d said the Insull\nannouncement, \u201cand they have indi\ncated that the responses will be practi\ncally universal. Girls and boys, men\nand women, will come in.\u201d\nIt was estimated by one company\nofficial that the gift would amount to\nmore than SIOO,OOO per month.\nIt will be distributed through relief\nj organizations to be selected later.\nCOL. CHEEVER BURIED\nWITH MILITARY HONORS\nRetired Cavalry Officer Took Part\nin Many Conflicts\u2014Held Con\ngressional Medal.\nMilitary ceremonies marked the burial\nin the Arlington National Cemetery this\nafternoon of Col. Benjamin Harrison\nCheever, a retired Cavalry officer, who\ni died at his home, in Atlantic Cit, N. J.,\nlast Tuesday in his eightieth year.\nBorn in this city, he was commis\nsioned a second lieutenant of the 6th\nCavalry in August, 1876, and saw active\nservice in several Indian campaigns in\nthe Far West, the Spanish War of 1898,\nthe Philippine insurrection which fol\nlowed and the World War.\nWhile serving with the 6th Cavalry\nat White River, S. Dak., in 1891, he dis\ntinguished himself by bravery against a\nlarge band of hostile Sioux Indians by\nheading the advance across the partly\nfrozen river and rescuing another troop\nof his regiment, which had been sur\nrounded by the Indians. The ther\nmometer registered 20 degrees below\nzero at the time. Col. Cheever and his\nsmall party had to break through the\nIce to cross the river with their mounts.\nCol. Cheever was awarded the Congres\nsional Medal of Honor for his bravery\nand services on that occasion.\nAt the outbreak of the World War\nCol. Cheever, then on the retired list,\nvolunteered his services and rendered\nvaluable aid in recrult>g at Savannah\nand Atlanta, Ga, Surviving him are\nhis widow, Mrs. Cora Chapman Cheever,\nand a daughter, Mrs. Syewart C. Maxey\nof Jacksonville, Fla.\nStart Open-Air Mnsenm.\nKOENIGSBERG, Germany (JP). \u2014The\nlittle town of Oeorgenswaldt acquired\nthe first pre-historlc open air museum\nin the world when a grave more than\n2,500 years old was opened and found\nto possess an Interior architecture un\nequaled by any similar find in East\nPrussia. The tomb Is to ba open to\nthe public.\nI\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON, Da C\u201e FRIDAY, OCTOBER 24, M\nr\nJHH\nPOSTMASTER W. M. MOONEY.\nholidays, was S3O, a sum that would\ngo a long way, Mr. Mooney thinks, in\nthe household of the unemployed man\ntoday.\nMr. Mooney has instructed his per\nsonnel office to question each applicant\nfor Christmas work to determine\nwhether he is employed, in an effort\nI to weed out those who are not tiepnd\nent upon the work for their living.\nParticular attention will be paid to\nweeding out those applicants who, he\n1 says, aTe working in business houses\nabout the city and who have been in\nthe habit of saving their vacations un\ntil the Christmas time so they can get\njobs at the post office.\n\u201cThis is a time,\u201d he said, \u201cwheh the\nman with a job should stand aside\nand let the man without a job earn\nwhat he can.\u201d\nTHE WEATHER\nDistrict of Columbia\u2014Fair and slight\nly colder tonight, minimum temperature\nabout 25 degrees: tomorrow fair \u2014gentle\nto moderate west and northwest winds.\nMaryland and Virginia\u2014Cloudy and\ncolder tonight; tomorrow fair; fresh\nwest and northwest winds.\nWest Virginia\u2014Fair, slightly colder\ntonight; tomorrow fair.\nRecord for 24 Hours.\nThermometer p.m., 56; 8 p.m., 50;\n12 midnight, 47; 4 a.m., 43; 8 am., 45;\nnoon, 49.\nBarometer\u20144 p.m., 30.09; 8 p.m.,\n30.05; 12 midnight, 29.94; 4 a.m., 29.87;\n8 a.m., 29.87; noon, 29.86.\nHighest temperature, 57, occurred at\n2 p.m. yesterday.\nLowest temperature, 42, occurred at\n4:30 a.m. today.\nTemperature same date last year\u2014\nHighest, 61; lowest, 41.\nTide Tables.\n(Furnished by United States Coast and\nGeodetic Survey.)\nToday\u2014Low tide, 4:06 a.m. and\n4:16 p.m.; high tide, 9:40 a.m. and\n10:01 p.m.\nTomorrow\u2014Low tide, 4:53 a.m. and\n5:01 p.m.; high tide, 10:26 a.m. and\n10:46 p.m.\nThe Sun and Moon.\nToday\u2014Sun rose 6:26 a.m.; sun sets\n5:18 p.m.\nTomorrow\u2014Sun rises 6:25 a.m.; sun\nsets 5:17 p.m.\nMoon rises 8:25 a.m.; sets 6:17 p.m.\nAutomobile lamps to be lighted one\nhalf hour after sunset.\nCondition of the Waters.\nPotomac and Shenandoah Rivers\nclear this morning.\nWeather in Various Cities.\n1 tsH\nStations. j* S.| 2* o~ weather\ns** S-\nr\nAbilene, Tex.... 30.16 58 40 0.02 Clear\nAlbany, N. Y.. 29 82 54 44 0.10 Raining\nAtlanta, Ga.... 30.00 64 50 0.01 Cloudy\nAtlantic City .29 82 56 46 002 Cloudy\nBaltimore, Md.. 29 86 58 44 0.01 Pt.cloudy\nBirmingham ...30 04 70 50 0.02 Cloudy\nBlamarclc. N D. 29.96 58 28 Clear\nBoston, Mass... 29 86 58 46 ....Raining\nBuffalo, N. Y.. 29 84 46 38 0.12 Raining\nCharleston. S.C. 29 94 64 56 Cloudy\nChicago, 111 30 04 46 38 ....Cloudy\nCincinnati, Ohio 30 08 42 36 0.04 Pt.cloudy\nCleveland. Ohio. 29 94 50 42 Cloudy\nColumbia. S C. 29 96 64 50 001 Pt.cloudy\nDenver, C 010... 30.04 60 36 ....Clear\nDetroit. Mich..\nEl Paso. Tex... 30 14 74 48 Clear\nGalveston. Tex. 30 06 76 60 022 Cloudy\nHelena, Mont... 29 84 52 38 Pt.cloudy\nHuron, 8. Dak 30 08 54 28 Pt cloudy\nIndlanapolls.lnd 30.08 44 36 Clear\nJacksonville. Fla. 29 96 70 60 0.16 Raining\nKansas City. Mo. 30.16 54 40 ....Clear\nIkJS Angeles 29 92 92 56 Clear\nI/iulsyille. Ky.. 30 10 46 40 0.04 Pt.cloudy\nMiami. Fla 29.92 80 74 Cloudy\nNew Orleans... 29 94 72 66 001 Cloudy\nNew York, N Y 29 80 56 46 002 Raining\nOklahoma City. 30 20 56 40 Clear\nOmaha. Nebr.. 30 14 56 32 ....Clear\nPhiladelphia 29 82 56 44 0.01 Cloudy\nPhoenix. Ariz... 29 92 90 52 ...Clear\nPittsburgh, Pa.. 29 94 44 36 0.14 Cloudy\nPortland. Me... 29.90 52 38 Raining\nPortland, Oreg. 29.94 56 54 0.18 Clear\nRaleigh. N. c... 29 90 56 44 0.10 Pt.cloudy\nSalt Lake City. 30 04 66 44 Clear\nSan Antonio.... 30 14 70 48 0.98 Clear\nSan Diego. Calil 29 94 70 54 ....Cloudy\nSan Francisco... 29 98 68 54 ....Clear\n8t Louis. M 0... 30.12 50 38 0.01 Clear\nSt. Paul. Minn.. 30.12 48 34 Clear\nSeattle. Wash 29.90 54 50 038 Raining\nSpokane. Wash. 29.98 56 38 0.02 Pt.cloudy\nTampa, Pla 29 94 76 66 0.06 Raining\nWASH., D. C... 29.87 57 42 ....Pt.cloudy\nFOREIGN.\n(7 a.m.; Greenwich time, today.)\nStations. Temperature Weather.\nLondon. England 44 Clear\nParis, France 54 Clear\nBerlin. Germany 44 Clear\nBrest. France...- 54 Cloudy\nStockholm. Sweden 48 Clear\n(Noon. Greenwich time, today.)\nHorta <rayal), Azores 62 Cloudy\n(Current observations.)\nHamilton. Bermuda...... 68 Cloudy\nHavana. Cuba 72 Part cloudy\nColon. Canal Zone 78 Part cloudy\nINDUSTRIAL 1\nBANKING\niSai It is not necessary r|\nto have had an I\nU Account at this Bank\nto Borrow\n[easy to pay\nMonthly\nDepont\nLo\u00abn\u00ab Months\n$l2O SIO.OO\nSIBO $15.00\n$240 $20.00\nS3OO $25.00\n$360 $30.00\nI $540 $45.00\n$1,200 SIOO.OO\nH $6,000 $500.00\nI\nIF THE MORRIS T|\nPLAN BANK\nUnder Supervision U. S. Treasury\n1403 H Street N.W.\niJOE AIELLO. RIVAL\nOF CAPONE. KILLED\nPartner of \u201cBugs\u201d Moran\nTrapped as Retreat Is Cut\nOff by Gangsters.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, October 24\u2014Gangster\nguns, silent in Chicago for some time,\nopened up Rgaln last night and removed\nJoe Aiello, one of the few remaining\nrivals of Alfonse Capone, from the pic\nture of Chicago's crime.\nAiello, reputed alcohol king, partner\nof George (Bugs) Moran and with\nMoran listed by the Chicago Crime\nCommission as a \u201cpublic enemy,\u201d was\nshot and killed by a gang of men, num\nber unknown, as he left the apartment\nof Patsy Prestogiacomo, an Importer,\nin North Kolmar avenue.\nSeventeen or more bullets were fired\ninto the gang leader f.om machine and\nother guns secreted in three different\npositions as Aiello walked into what the\npolice said was one of the most\nelaborate assassination plots in gangland\nhistory.\nFound Himself Trapped.\nAs he stepped out of the Presto\ngiacomo apartment, presumably to\nenter a cab that was waiting to\ntake him and Prestogiacomo to his\nhome, machine-gun fire opened from\na third-floor window of an apart\nment across the street. Aiello turned\nand fled back into the vestibule and\nattempted to arouse some one in the\napartment. Finding his way blocked by\nlocked doors, he fled into the apartment\ncourtyard, only to meet the fire of\nmachme guns coming from a window'\nof a builuing to the north. Fleeing to\nthe rear of the court in an attempt to\nescape over a back fence, he ran into\na fusillade of shots coming from the\nbasmeent of the building housing the\nPresto apartment.\nA police sergeant and James Duane,\na cab driver, wno had responded to a\nprevious call for Mrs. Prestogiacomo for\na cab to take Aiello and her husband to\nAiello\u2019s home, took the wounded man\nto a hospital, but he died before his\narrival.\nThus was added another victim to the\nlong list of gangsters slain in the in\nternecine strife that had Its beginning\nin the slaying of Dion O'Bannion in\n1924 and whlcn Included the machlne-\nI gun slaying ot seven followers of Moran\na year ago last St. Valentine\u2019s day in\na North Clark street garage.\nCapone Is Suspected.\nVarious theories and beliefs w r ere ad\nvanced by the authorities in a possible\nexplanation of gangland's latest slay\ning. One of these was that Aiello's\ndeath might nave had some connection\nwith the slaying last June 9 of Alfred\nLlngle, a reporter for the Chicago Tri\nbune, known as a friend of Capcne.\nSome officials said they suspected\nCapone and mentioned the hostility be\ntween Aiello and Capone in support of\ntheir suspicions.\nOther theories were that Aiello\u2019s\nassassination might have been prompted\nby his wish to control the destinies of\nthe Unione Sicilian*, which was at one\ntime dominated by his irienu, uouy\nLambardo, who was killed at Madison\nand Dearborn streets some years ago.\nAnother report was that detectives had\nhinted that a New York gang, headed\nby a man known as \u201cJoe the Boss\u201d and\nbelieved connected with the Unione,\nmight have been involved.\nShortly after the slaying two men\nwere reported seen running from the\nfront of the west end building, one of\nthem carrying a machine gun. They\nfled in a sedan. A Tew seconds later\nanother machine, bearing two men, was\nreported to have followed the sedan.\nLater an automobile, with Its license\nplates removed and Its engine numbers\nobliterated, was found burning in an\nother section of the city.\nThe police said they learned that the\napartment from which the firing first\nbegan was rented by a young man 10\ndays ago, indicating that Aiello's death\nhad been plotted long in advance of\nlast night's shooting.\nAiello was 39 years of age, which Is\nconsidered old for a man engaged in\ngangland activities. He was the second\nof the \u201cpublic enemies\" to meet death\nsince the Crime Commission issued\nlist of undesirables last ApriL The\nother was Jack Zuta, wh v.\u00bb*\nlast August In a resort in Wisconsin.\ny H UMML\nFranc\u2019s present \"Love Gems\u201d\u2014dia\nmond ring creations that fairly breathe\nSMARTNESS! All Washington is stir-\nThe Call O\u2019 Love SSA. red to a buying pitch\u2014And why notT\npSi \"Love Gems\u201d are NEW DIFFER\nfySI\\\\ ENT UNUSUAL\u2014and at prices that\n$2.00 Weakly jClll VX are ineom parable.\nWe want everyone to enjoy\nBlending in perfect har- Franc\u2019s easy credit plan. It allows\nmony the 5 brilliant, bit- term. It suit YOUR convenience.\nA New \u201cLove-Gem\u201d 17-Jewel movement fold filled\ndustite curved-to-fit-the-wrist case.\na \u2713X Open link band included.^\nThi\u00bb is one example of\nthe UNUSUAL \u201cLove Gem\u201d ym. am\ndiamond rings. 12 Sparkling Ladies\u2019 s'7^7*so\ngems form a colorful cluster BLJLOVA\naround the perfect cut center\ndiamond. Artistically hand Beautifully designed r.lgin case\nengraved 18-kt. white gold protects a guaranteed accurate move\nmounting. ment. Link bracelet to match at\nS 'l T 110 Xtf yy f'l\nThe \u201cSTARBEAM\u201d the store that\u2019s forging ahead\nstands bv I 1\nW v I B\nand smartlv engraved mount- lijl\u00dfM|BHsH\u00df\u00df\u00df\u00a7BMM|(li|BS|B\u00abli^^\ning are UNUSUAL.\na Week\nMrs. Doran Visions\n\u201cPerfect Hostess\u201d\nAs Law-Observing\nA new idea of the perfect mod\nern hostess is soon to be launched\nby Mrs. James M. Doran, wife of\nthe commissioner of Industrial al\ncohol, who concocted the non\nalcoholic cocktail.\nHer presentation of the new\nhostess will be made at the na\ntional convention of the Women\u2019s\nChristian Temperance Union in\nHouston, Tex., November 14. Mrs.\nDoran has evolved the idea as a\nresult of a Nation-wide symposium\nof women.\nIn contrast to the perfect host\ness of years gone by, whose chief\nI duty was to please her guests, the\nnew 1931 pattern of hospitality\nchosen by the temperance women\nwill make her guests\u2019 desires, if\nneerssary, subordinate.\nShe will, first, put her guests at\nease and make them feel at home;\n1 second, so tactfully but firmly Im\nprint her own personality on any\nj function In her home that her\nguests will take what she serves\nand like it; third, dispense only\nthe hospitality which conforms\nwith the laws of her city and\nState.\nA new slogan will be launched\nat the convention by Mrs. Doran.\nIt Is \u201cFill the National Goblet\nLegitimately.\"\nI\nSCHWAB PREDICTS\nBUSINESS REVIVAL\nI\n\n1 Greatest Prosperity Era in Ameri\ncan History Is Ex\npected.\nNEW YORK, October 24 (>P).\u2014Charles\nM. Schwab told the American Iron and\nSteel Institute today that when the\nbusiness revival comes, as come it must,\n\"it will bring to this country a larger\ni measure of prosperity than the Amer\nican people have ever before known.\u201d\nHe looks forward to 1932 as \u201canother\nrecord year.\u201d\nHe said the \u201clevel-headed way In\nwhich business In general has weathered\nthe current recession is most assuring,\ni and shows that the underlying founda\ntions of Its structure are sound.\n\u201cSome are inclined to think because\nbusiness pauses from time to time In\nits forward course, that our natural\ni optimism has somehow been tricked,\u201d\nMr. Schwab said. \u2019\u2019At the first signs\nof recession, the timid become pessi\nmistic. Assurance gives way to uncer\ntainty and fear. Those with faith and\ncourage based upon known facts refuse\nto accept this philosophy; they recog\nnize that such pauses make for sounder\nprogress. It is only in a stagnant civ\nilization that changes do not occur.\"\nAs for the steel industry, Mr. Schwab\nsaid, it Is within 5 per cent of the\naverage production for the past 10\nyears. The jteel Industry's policy par\nceling out work and maintaining wage\nscales has tended to keep the Industry\nstable, he said, and has prevented far\nworse conditions from prevailing.\nThere was some price \"sharpshooting\"\nwhen the recession first came, he said,\nbut this has been largely eliminated,\nand price and production stabilized.\nUNEXPECTED FLIGHT DELAYS\nWEDDING OF ANACOSTIA PILOT\nLicense Is Issued After Closing Hours, When Flyer\nReturns From Hartford Too Late.\nFast work on the part of himself and\nhis friends made possible the marriage\nlast night of Chief Aviation Pilot Leon\nard C. McAllister, Anacostla Naval Air\nStation, after he had been delayed by\nan unexpected flight to Hatrford, Conn.,\nreturning here after the close of the\nMarriage License Bureau.\nMcAllister\u2019s bride. Miss Generose\nDickens, 24 years old, arrived by rail\nfrom Long Beach, Calif., while McAl\nlister was in Hartford, where he had\nbeen sent to ferry back a new plane.\nMcAllister did not land here until after\n3 o\u2019clock and the License Bureau was\nclosed when he arrived at the court\nhouse. When he explained his predlca\ni ment, however, the license was issued\nafter hours.\nBILLION FLOOD AID\nPROGRAM IS URGED\nBoston Mayor\u2019s Mississippi\nValley Plan Attracts\nHoover\u2019s Interest.\nExpenditure of a billion dollars for\nflood control and associated hydro\nelectric plants In the Mississippi River\nValley was utged by Mayor James M.\nCurley of Boston In a conference yes\nterday with President Hoover, Secretary\nof War Hurley and Gen. Charles P.\nSummerall. chief of staff.\nThe Boston mayor sketched the possi\n\u2019bility of direct shipment of cereals, cot\nton, steel and coal through the States\nalong the Mississippi River, contending\nthat this commeice, coupled with cheap\nwater transportation, would undoubt\nedly prove so attractive to private capi\ntal that an amount at least twice as\ngreat as the initial investment would be\nexpended by private interests within a\nvery few years.\nThe President, it was said, showed so\nmuch interest in this proposal that he\nheartily approved Mayor Curley\u2019s effer\nto go Into the matter further with cabi\nnet officers, which the Boston mayor\ndid later with Secretary James J. Davis\nof the Department of Labor and Secre\ntary Lamont of the Department of\nCommerce. He agreed to supply both\nof these cabinet officers with a mass cf\ndata upon this subject.\nAs a result of Mayor Curley\u2019s confer\nence the Federal Government is about\nto turn over Governors Island to the\ncity of Boston for development of one\nof Irv- greatest airports In the world.\nThe development of this airport will\ncast upward of $20,000,000 and will fur\nnish employment for two years to si,me\n2.000 men, 500 of whom will be put\nwork probably next month, according to\nMayor Curley.\nIn 1902 the Federal Government\nturned Governors Island over to the\nBoston municipality, but requisitioned\nit during the World War. The pro\nposed lease will reserve to the United\nStates Government the right to com\nmandeer the Island and airport devel\nopment at any time it is needed for\nnational defense.\nOREGON LOAN BANK\nWILL AID JOBLESS\nBy the Associated Press.\nPORTLAND. Oreg., October 24.\nOrganization of a workingmen\u2019s loan\nbank with a capital of $150,000 or more,\nto be used for unemployment relief, was\nproposed yesterday by Ben Selling,\nchairman of Portland\u2019s Unemployment\nCommittee.\nThe bank\u2019s funds would be loaned to\nmarried men with families who have\nlived in Portland six months or more.\nThe loans would not exceed $25 a\nmonth and would continue not more\nthan five months. They would be re\npayable at $2.50 a week, beginning\nMarch 15, 1931.\nSelling said his bank plan would care\nfor 1,500 families during the Winter.\nHe believed 95 per cent of the loans\nwould be repaid.\nIn his absence his friends had wel\ncomed the bride and made the last\nminute arrangements and at 7:30 the\ncouple was married by Rev. Joseph V.\nBuckley, pastor of St. Francis Xavier\nChurch, at his home. 2800 Pennsylvania\navenue southeast. Chief Aviation Pilot\nPhillip I. Gunn of the Anacostla sta\ntion was best man and Mrs. Gunn at\ntended the bride.\nMcAllister\u2019s home is in Jersey City\nHeights, N. J. He met Miss Dickens\nwhile on duty in California six years\nago. They will make their home here,\nat 1338 Ridge place southeast.\n\nF. W. Jeffs, the new mayor of Wat\nford, England, is a crack rifle shot.\n1 IB KEEP JOBS\nBY O\u2019CONNOR ORDER!\n250 Washingtonians Affected\nby Fleet Corporation\nPolicy Suspension.\nAnother step to alleviate unemploy\nment conditions in Washington and the\nNation generally was taken yesterday\nby Chairman T. V. O\u2019Connor of the\nShipping Board in deciding to suspend\nthe discharge of about 700 employes\nof the Fleet Corporation in various parts\nof the country and abroad, 250 of them\nin Washington.\nLocally, stenographers and clerks were\naffected mostly by the order that went I\nout last month under the name of\nJ. Caldwell Jenkins, acting presiden*.\nof the Fleet Corporation, who planned\nto reduce the numbers gradually. Under\nthis announced program, the jobs are\nsafe during the Winter, at least, and\nofficials asserted today that the reduc-\ntion program has not yet been put into\neffect.\nThe Jenkins order was brought about\nThe World-Renowned\nBolton\nWorsteds\npresented by Bond for the\nfirst time anywhere, at this\namazingly low figure\n\u202225\nwith two trousers\nThe distinguished style of Bond London-\nDesigned Fashions has been accepted as a\nmatter of course, by well-groomed men. So,\nwe desire rather to emphasize the matchless\nvalue of these two-trouser suits, faultlessly\ntailored in rich-textured Bolton Worsteds.\nThey have those subdued colorings and rare\npattern-designs characteristic of costly fabrics.\nDouble-weaving has endowed them with a\nlong, healthy life. Bond master-needlework\ngives them a trim, perfectly fitted drape. They\nare the sort of suits that will make you say\n\"that was money well spent.\" For the\nfirst time, anywhere, Bond presents them, at\n$25, with two trousers.\nUse Bond Ten Payment Service!\n1335 F ST.\nIn the renrgnnlcetidta of the worts of th*\ncorporation and wfts directed at getting\nthe Federal Governments out of ths\nshipping business. Chairman O'Connor\nsaid today that the Shipping Board\ni would allow the proposed reduction pro-\nl gram to remain inactive at present and\nJ do nothing about it.\nPROMINENT ENGINEER\nFOUND SHOT TO DEATH\nBy the Associated Press.\nATLANTA, Ga., October 24.\u2014Charles\nCecil Case, prominent Atlanta engineer\nand building contractor, was found shot\nto death on the banks of Peach Tree\nCreek early today. Members of the\nfamily said he had been despondent\nI over ill-hraltli.\nA pistol, with oils chamb r empty,\nlay nearby. Police who found the bndy\ni said it apparently had plunged from a\nbridge to the bank of the creek, 20\nfort below.\nA search was under way for Case,\nwho failed to return heme Thursday\nnight.\nHis firm built much of the Atlanta\nwatcrwoiks system. His construction of\na feur-mile water -supply tunn-i at\ni Charleston. S. C.. was said by engines\nto have been one of his outstanding\n1 pieces of work.\nHr was 4S years old and was a native\ni of Goshen. Ind.","height":"25365","width":"19827"}}
